{"id": "duc04-testb-6:0#0", "contents": "North Korea is facing its fourth winter of severe food shortages, with its population suffering from malnutrition and increased risk of dying from curable illnesses. Senior Red Cross officials have warned against international complacency and hostility towards the country, as the food crisis continues with little sign of improvement. The Red Cross' undersecretary of disaster relief, Margareta Wahlstrom, recently returned from a week-long inspection of the agency's operations in North Korea, where she witnessed the devastating effects of the slow-motion famine. The capital, Pyongyang, receives electricity only half of the time, and the elderly population shows signs of long-term hunger, with many appearing swollen."}
